<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>

<section xml:id="sec-s01e01" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
  <title>Episode 1: Addition and Subtraction</title>
<assemblage>
  <title>Episode 1 Learning Goals</title>
  <p>
    <ul>
      <li>
        <p>
          Describe the physical action represented by addition and subtraction. 
        </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>
          Interpret the words used to indicate addition and subtraction. 
        </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>
          Interpret the symbols used to indicate addition and subtraction.  
        </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>
          Perform addition and subtraction in real-world contexts. 
        </p>
      </li>
    </ul>
  </p>
  </assemblage>

  <assemblage>
    <title>Episode 1 Terminology</title>
    <p>
      <ul>
        <li>
          <p>
            Sum
          </p>
        </li>
      
      <li>
          <p>
            Difference
          </p>
        </li>
        </ul>
    </p>
  </assemblage>

  <assemblage>
    <title>Episode 1 Key Symbols</title>
    <p>
     <md>
      + \hspace{1.0in}\text{as in}\,\, 3 + 2
     </md>
      </p>
      <p>
        <md>
          - \hspace{1.0in}\text{as in}\,\, 4 - 1
        </md>
        </p>
  </assemblage>

      <definition xml:id="def-addition">
      <statement>
        <p>
        <alert>Addition</alert> is the operation that corresponds to combining piles of similar objects.
        Addition is represented using the symbol <m>+</m> (“plus”). 
        </p>
      </statement>
    </definition>

    <example>
      <p>
        What is <m>4+2</m>?
      </p>
      <p>
      Solution: Create a pile containing 4 objects. Create a second pile containing 2 objects. Put those piles together and count the number of objects you have in total.
      </p>
      <p>
    🟢🟢🟢🟢  +  🟢🟢  =  🟢🟢🟢🟢🟢🟢
    </p>
    <p>
      In total, we have 6 objects, so: <m>4+2=6</m>
    </p>
    </example>
    <example>
    <p>
      If you have 3 slices of leftover pepperoni pizza and 2 slices of leftover cheese pizza, how many slices of pizza do you have in total?
    </p>
    <p>
      Solution: Since we’re putting together two piles of pizza slices, this is an addition problem. Specifically, this is the problem
      <md>
        3+2
      </md>
      We can answer the problem by counting: 🍕🍕🍕 + 🍕🍕=🍕🍕🍕🍕🍕
    </p>
    <p>
      In other words, we have a total of <m>3+2 = 5</m> slices of pizza.
    </p>
    </example>

  <assemblage>
  <title>Notice Something Neat</title>
  
  
    <p>
      You can change the order of the numbers in an addition problem and still get the same answer!
    </p>
    <p>
      <m>4+1=5 </m> because 🟢🟢🟢🟢 + 🟢 = 🟢🟢🟢🟢🟢
    </p>
    <p>
      <m>1+4=5 </m> because 🟢 + 🟢🟢🟢🟢 = 🟢🟢🟢🟢🟢
    </p>
  </assemblage>

    <p>
      For problems involving larger numbers, you can use the <tag>+</tag> button on your calculator to perform addition.
    </p>

  
  <example>
    <p>
    You have $214 in your bank account, and then you deposit another $1371. Now how much money do you have in your account?
    </p>
    <p>
      Solution: Since you’re combining two piles of money, this is an addition problem, specifically the problem
      <md>
        214+1371
      </md>
      We can use the <m>+</m> button on our calculator to find the answer to this problem:
      <md>
        214+1371=1585
      </md>
      So that means we have $1585 in the bank account now.
    </p>
  </example>

<p>
  There are a couple of common key words that indicate that we need to perform addition. These include:
  <ul>
    <li>
      <p>
        Total
      </p>
    </li>
    <li>
      <p>
        Combine
      </p>
    </li>
    <li>
      <p>
        Sum
      </p>
    </li>
  </ul>
</p>

<example>
<p>
  What is the sum of 8 and 3?
</p>
<p>
  Solution: This is asking us to add 8 and 3.
  <md>
    8+3 = 11
  </md>
</p>
</example>

<definition xml:id="def-subtraction">
  <statement>
    <p>
      <alert>Subtraction</alert> is the operation that corresponds to removing objects from a pile.
  Subtraction is represented using the symbol <m>-</m> (“minus” or “take away”). 
    </p>
  </statement>
</definition>

<example>
  <p>
    What is <m>5-2</m>?
  </p>
  <p>
    Solution: Create a pile containing 5 objects. Remove 2 objects from that pile. Then count the number of objects you have left. 
  </p>
  <p>
    🟢🟢🟢🟢🟢  -  🟢🟢  =  🟢🟢🟢
  </p>
  <p>
    3 objects remain in the pile, so: <m>5-2=3</m>.
  </p>
</example>

<example>
  <p>
    If you have 8 eggs and use 3 of them in a recipe, how many eggs do you have left? 
  </p>
  <p>
    Solution: Since we’re removing eggs from a pile, this is a subtraction problem. <m>8-3</m> We can answer the problem by counting:
  </p>
  <p>
    🥚🥚🥚🥚🥚🥚🥚🥚 - 🥚🥚🥚 = 🥚🥚🥚🥚🥚
  </p>
  <p>
    In other words, we have <m>8-3=5</m> remaining eggs.
  </p>
</example>

<p>
  For problems involving larger numbers, you can use the <tag>-</tag> button on your calculator to perform addition.
  </p>
  
  <example>
  <p>
    You have $523 in your bank account, and then you spend $138 on groceries. Now how much money do you have in your account?
  </p>
  <p>
    Solution: Since you’re taking away money for a pile of money, this is a subtraction problem, specifically the problem
    <md>
      523 - 138
    </md>
    We can use the + button on our calculator to find the answer to this problem:
    <md>
      523 - 138 = 385
    </md>
    So that means we have $385 in the bank account now.
  </p>
  </example>

  <p>
    There are a couple of common key words that indicate that we need to perform subtraction. These include:
    <ul>
      <li>
        <p>
          Remove
        </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>
          Take Away
        </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>
          Decrease
        </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <p>
          Difference
        </p>
      </li>
    </ul>
  </p>

  <example>
  <p>
   What is the difference between 10 and 4? 
  </p>
  <p>
    Solution: This is asking us to subtract 10 and 4.
    <md>
      10-4=6.
    </md>
    </p>
    </example>


<worksheet xml:id="ws-s01e1">
  <title>Episode 1 Practice Problems</title>
  <exercise>
  <introduction>
    <p>
       Calculate the following values by hand.
    </p>
  </introduction>
       
      <task workspace="0.5in">
      <statement>
        <p>
          <md> 9-5 = \hspace{1.5in} 1+7= \hspace{1.5in} 2+5=\hspace{1.5in}</md>
        </p>
      </statement>
    </task>
    <task workspace="0.5in">
      <statement>
        <p>
          <md> 6+2 = \hspace{1.5in} 5+4= \hspace{1.5in} 9-1=\hspace{1.5in}</md>
        </p>
      </statement>
    </task>
    <task workspace="0.5in">
      <statement>
        <p>
          <md> 8-3 = \hspace{1.5in} 7-6= \hspace{1.5in} 4+3=\hspace{1.5in}</md>
        </p>
      </statement>
    </task>
  </exercise>
  
  <exercise>
  <introduction>
    <p>
      Calculate the following values using a calculator. 
    </p>
  </introduction>
       <task workspace="0.75in">
        <statement>
          <p>
             <md>702-458 = \hspace{2.2in} 900-374=\hspace{2.2in}</md>
          </p>
        </statement>
      </task>
      <task workspace="0.75in">
        <statement>
          <p>
             <md>1236+789 = \hspace{2.1in} 4508+2967=\hspace{2.2in}</md>
          </p>
        </statement>
      </task>
   
  </exercise>

  <exercise>
  <introduction>
    <p>
      Answer these word problems
    </p>
  </introduction>
    <task workspace="1.0in">
      <statement>
        <p>
          Mia has 3 apples. Her friend gives her 4 more apples. How many apples does Mia have now?
        </p>
      </statement>
    </task>
    <task workspace="1.0in">
      <statement>
        <p>
          There are 8 pencils on a desk. 5 pencils are taken away. How many pencils are left on the desk?
        </p>
      </statement>
    </task>
    <task workspace="1.0in">
      <statement>
        <p>
          2 birds are sitting on a fence. 5 more birds fly over and land on the fence. How many birds are on the fence in total?
        </p>
      </statement>
    </task>
    <task workspace="1.0in">
      <statement>
        <p>
          Leo has 9 cookies. He eats 3 of them. How many cookies does Leo have left?
        </p>
      </statement>
    </task>
  </exercise>

  <exercise>
  <introduction>
    <p>
      Interpret the key words to answer the following questions. 
    </p>
  </introduction>
    
  <task workspace="1.0in">
    <statement>
      <p>
        What is the <alert>sum</alert> of 3 and 5?
      </p>
    </statement>
  </task>
  <task workspace="1.0in">
    <statement>
      <p>
        What is the <alert>difference</alert> between 9 and 4?
      </p>
    </statement>
  </task>
  <task workspace="1.0in">
    <statement>
      <p>
        Find the <alert>sum</alert> of 6 and 2?
      </p>
    </statement>
  </task>
  <task workspace="1.0in">
    <statement>
      <p>
        Find the <alert>difference</alert> between 8 and 3?
      </p>
    </statement>
  </task>
  </exercise>
</worksheet>
</section>